## Research Agenda

My research lies at the intersection of **experimental economics**, **behavioral economics**, and **political economy**. I study how individuals process information and make decisions under uncertainty, using a combination of **experimental methods** and **theoretical modeling**. 

My work focuses on understanding the cognitive and motivational mechanisms that drive belief formation and choice, particularly in environments characterized by risk, ambiguity, and ideologically charged information.

## Current Research Focus

### Artificial Intelligence, Misinformation, and Motivated Reasoning

This project examines how **AI-generated misinformation** and **AI-based detection signals** interact with **ideological congruence bias** in news classification. Using a within-subject laboratory experiment, I investigate how individuals update their beliefs when exposed to both news content and corrective AI signals. The results show that while AI detection can improve accuracy on average, its effectiveness is substantially reduced when individuals exhibit strong motivated reasoning and congruence bias.Moreover, the explicit introduction of AI in the information environment increases general skepticism toward news.

**Status:** Working Paper

### Salience and Strategy in Stochastic Choice

(with G. Coricelli, D. Di Cagno and G. Taurino)

This project investigates deliberate randomization in stochastic choice environments. We study how individuals randomize choices deliberately when salient attributes are in conflict.

**Status:** Under Revision

